07402nam a22009615i 9781978824591DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97819788245917 a10.36019/97819788245912doi  a(DE-B1597)647576  a(OCoLC)1355222417  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.77086/642223//eng/20221005eng02aA Pill for Promiscuity :bGay Sex in an Age of Pharmaceuticals /ced. by Jeffrey Escoffier, Andrew R. Spieldenner. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (142 p.) :b18 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQ+ Public00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Foreword -- tIntroduction: Why Promiscuity Matters -- t1 Notes on Promiscuity, 1988 -- tPerspective: Fear -- tIntroduction -- t2 Safe -- t3 How I Learned to Stop Worrying, or the Straight Panic Defense -- tPerspective: Sex -- tIntroduction -- t4. Reluctant Objects: HIV Prevention and the Problem of Sexual Pleasure -- t5 Learning How to Fuck on PrEP -- t6 Gay Sex Is Our Superpower -- tPerspective: Pharma -- tIntroduction -- t7. “Heard about It Before, but Don’t Know Where to Get It”: A Black Gay Man’s Journey to Securing PrEP -- t8 PrEP in the Porn World -- t9. Auto-Pharmakon: Prescribing Utopia -- tPerspective: Trauma and Healing -- t10. S(t)imulation -- t11. Playing in the Shadows: Cycles of Trauma -- t12. When We Touch: A Reading on Queer Intimacies -- tEpilogue: Promiscuity for the Non-Promiscuous -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor a generation of gay men who came of age in the 1980s and 1990s, becoming sexually active meant confronting the dangers of catching and transmitting HIV. In the 21st century, however, the development of viral suppression treatments and preventative pills such as PrEP and nPEP has massively reduced the risk of acquiring HIV. Yet some of the stigma around gay male promiscuity and bareback sex has remained, inhibiting open dialogues about sexual desire, risk, and pleasure. A Pill for Promiscuity brings together academics, artists, and activists—from different generations, countries, ethnic backgrounds, and HIV statuses—to reflect on how gay sex has changed in a post-PrEP era. Some offer personal perspectives on the value of promiscuity and the sexual communities it fosters, while others critique unequal access to PrEP and the increased role Big Pharma now plays in gay life. With a diverse group of contributors that includes novelist Andrew Holleran, trans scholar Lore/tta LeMaster, cartoonist Steve MacIsaac, and pornographic film director Mister Pam, this book asks provocative questions about how we might reimagine queer sex and sexuality in the 21st century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agay, gay culture, gay men, LGBT rights, LGBT promiscuity, sex lives, sexuality, fetish, BDSM, HIV epidemic, spread of HIV, HIV prevention, pharmacy, medicine, AIDS prevention, abstinence sex education, sex education, sexual health, healthy sex practices, LGBT stigma.1 aCrichton, E. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDore, Pam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscoffier, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscoffier, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFelsenthal, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Nic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela